Dear Lisa,

Thank you for reaching out and for your interest in the impact of social work at the community level. I’m happy to share some reflections that might be helpful for your upcoming Urban Times feature.

Key day-to-day challenges
1. Limited, often short-term funding that makes it hard to sustain programs long enough to see systemic change.
2. Fragmented services—families may need housing, mental-health and employment support, yet each sits in a separate silo with its own paperwork and eligibility rules.
3. Burnout and vicarious trauma among practitioners. The pandemic amplified needs while shrinking resources, so protecting workers’ well-being has become part of the work itself.

Programs that have shown promise
• Community Youth Mentorship Circles – Pairing local high-school students with trained volunteer mentors from the same neighborhood. Since 2019 we’ve seen a 30 % increase in graduation rates among participants and a measurable drop in juvenile-court involvement.
• Integrated Service Hubs – A “one-door” model that co-locates social assistance, primary care and legal-aid clinics. Families can address multiple needs in one visit and providers share a common case file (with consent), which cuts duplication and improves outcomes.
• Culturally-rooted Mental-Health Outreach – Partnering with faith leaders and barbershops to host pop-up counseling sessions. Attendance and follow-through are far higher than at traditional clinics because the setting feels familiar and stigma is lower.

Where the role of social work is heading
• Prevention over crisis response: We’re investing more time in community organizing, tenant associations and school-based interventions to stop problems before they escalate.
• Data-informed practice: Using dashboards that combine public-health, housing and school data lets us target resources and demonstrate impact to funders.
• Policy advocacy: Direct service is still core, but social workers are increasingly at city-council hearings pushing for living-wage ordinances, eviction protections and equitable transit—all root factors in clients’ lives.
• Cross-sector collaboration: Partnerships with tech startups (for secure case-management apps) and local businesses (for supported employment pathways) are growing.

